  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Energy for Life: in defence of municipal policies that promote renewable and efficient energy</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This project aims to support low income rural farming communities in the state of Piaui, north east Brazil, to access sustainable energy systems, and thus improve their income generation and food sovereignty. Having solar panels will allow them to sell back surplus energy to the grid through an energy compensation policy. Additionally, they will have access to a rotating fund for equipment maintenance and investment in their productive activities. They will also have increased their technical knowledge on equipment maintenance, and be actively advocating for the rollout of pro-climate energy generation policies across their municipalities. 

This will be achieved via three key strategies and activities: solar panel installation adequate to communities&#x2019; energy needs for farming; community training on system use and maintenance and energy policies; and municipal-level advocacy to promote bills and policies that promote low income communities&#x2019; access to sustainable energy. 

The state of Piaui in the north east of Brazil is part of the semi-arid region of Brazil &#x2013; the largest of its kind in the world, with high rates of water shortages and droughts &#x2013; and is the poorest state in Brazil. Piaui has one of the biggest solar power generators in Brazil, which is exploited by large businesses, but small farmers and enterprises are excluded from using this energy, and the access that they do have is environmentally harmful, onerous and unviable for their activities (i.e. irrigation and food production). This project aims to support the cry of the earth and the cry of the poor through environmentally sustainable energy generation initiatives that will serve as a precedent for other similar communities throughout the north east.</narrative>
  </description>
